text:
Let $S = \{1, 2, \dots, n\}$. Then $a_i = i$ for $i=1, \dots, n$. We want to count the number of triples $(i, j, k)$ such that $1 \le i < j < k \le n$ and $2j = i+k$.
This implies that $i$ and $k$ have the same parity.
\begin{itemize}
    \item If $i$ is even, then $k$ is even. Let $i = 2m$ and $k = 2p$. Then $j = m+p$.
    \item If $i$ is odd, then $k$ is odd. Let $i = 2m-1$ and $k = 2p-1$. Then $j = m+p-1$.
\end{itemize}
